64-row spiral CT is the most advanced equipment in the world for diagnosing heart and brain blood vessel diseases, its unique non-invasive, highly efficient, accurate and 3D imaging technology has significant advantage in examining whether the artery stenosis, bypass, stent morphology in coronary artery and cardiac function analysis. It enables non-invasive examination of coronary artery and provides a safe, rapid and low cost screening method for diagnosing and general screening coronary heart disease.

Siemens 64-row 128-level spiral 4D CT is one of the imaging diagnosis devices. A unique fusion of the Galaxy platform, breaking the traditional technology bottlenecks and entering imaging new era of 4D imaging from two-dimensional, three-dimensional imaging, it can obtain a full phase dynamic vessel imaging and receive whole brain and liver perfusion with one scan, the machine has ultra-fast scanning capability, you can complete high-precision imaging examination of whole body from head to toe within a few seconds. it applies advanced magnetic suspension rack drive and unique zero trillion tube technology to achieve a rack rotation speed up to 0.3s, making the ability of the heart examination exceeding any 64-row CT machine.

Siemens Medical produced its first MR equipment for clinical use in 1980, and it has always been innovating in the field of technology, being a leader in MRI technology, particularly cutting-edge technology and trends of development. "Committed to innovation, focus on the future", Siemens Medical Solutions MRI Division has been adhering to this core concept.

A CT scan – or computed tomography scan – uses X-rays to produce images of a patient's body. But unlike a traditional two-dimensional X-ray, CT scans create incredibly detailed cross-sectional images by rotating around the body inside the gantry, which is the machine's large doughnut-shaped opening. A CT scanner is also unique because it can display a combination of soft tissue, bones and blood vessels in a single image. Because the heart is effectively imaged more than once (described above), cardiac CT angiography can result in a relatively high radiation exposure (around 12 millisievert), although newer acquisition protocols, have recently been developed which drastically reduce this exposure to around 1 mSv

I believe Siemens has the best quality images of any fluoroscopy equipment on the market.  Siemens equipment is relatively user friendly and easier to operate than many of its competitors' products. Our experience has been that Siemens fluoroscopy equipment is relatively reliable compared to other products we have used in the past (e.g., GE). The technicians responsible for repairs are very responsive to our needs, and the repairs are usually completed successfully within an acceptable time frame. We have just installed new flat panel Siemens fluoroscopy equipment that lowers the radiation dose considerably for patients used pulsed fluoroscopy and other technological advancements. There are problems, however, related to delays in obtaining exposures that can limit our ability to obtain satisfactory studies, especially of the esophagus. There also are some other issues with using the new flat panel equipment. I wish the engineers who designed this new equipment had spent more time working with radiologists to create equipment that better met our needs.

Siemens has a long track record of providing the highest quality equipment with the best spot images, a user friendly platform, and reasonable reliability. The new flat panel equipment has some advantages over the older digital Siemens units (such as lower radiation dose to the patient), but other issues related primarily to inordinate delays in obtaining image exposures that potentially may compromise GI fluoroscopic procedures.

Acuson was founded in 1979 with the introduction of the 128XP. By the ninties Acuson was producing the Sequoia, the highest selling ultrasound system on the market. In 2000 Acuson was purchased by Siemens ultrasound which continued producing the Sequoia 512 until 2008. The portable Acuson Cypress and Cypress Plus was also produced by Siemens ultrasound. The Acuson Sonoline Antares and Sonoline G50 were added later. The Acuson “X” series, X150 and X300 are the newest entry-level ultrasound systems from Siemens ultrasound.
